 PROJECT OVERVIEW
1.Project Idea Definition and Detailed Explanation

PROJECT TITLE: Mobile Banking Database System

DESCRIPTION OF THE PROBLEM
With the increasing use of mobile phones for financial services, banks must handle a
large amount of customer and transaction data efficiently. Mobile banking allows users 
to perform activities such as transferring money, checking balances, applying for loans, and paying bills using their mobile devices.

However, without a well-structured database system, it becomes difficult for banks to
manage customer information, financial accounts, transactions, and authentication data
securely and efficiently. Problems such as data redundancy, slow retrieval of
information, and poor transaction tracking may occur.
The proposed Mobile Banking Database System is designed to manage and organize banking 
information by storing structured data about clients, their accounts, wallets, devices,
transactions, and loans in a centralized database.

CONTEXT OF THE PROBLEM IN THE KENYAN ENVIRONMENT

In Kenya, mobile banking has become one of the most widely used financial technologies.
Many individuals rely on mobile platforms to perform financial transactions without 
visiting a physical bank branch. As the number of users grows, financial institutions 
must manage increasing volumes of data such as customer accounts, transaction records,
and authentication details.

While these services have improved convenience and financial access, they have also
introduced several challenges for banks and financial institutions.One major issue
in Kenya’s mobile banking sector is the increasing risk of fraud and security breaches.
Cybercriminals often attempt to gain unauthorized access to banking systems through
stolen credentials, phishing attacks, or compromised devices. 
Session expiration and authentication issues are also common in mobile banking platforms.
When users experience login failures or session interruptions during transactions,
it can lead to incomplete transactions.

Additionally, system failures and transaction delays can occur when large volumes of
users access mobile banking services simultaneously. If the database system is poorly
designed, it may struggle to process transactions quickly, resulting in slow responses
or system downtime.

Increase in non-performing loans. Many mobile banking platforms offer quick digital
loans to customers, but some borrowers fail to repay them on time due to the lack of
an effective system to track loan records, repayment schedules and loan status.
Customer support and account management is another challenge where many banks receive
numerous customer complaints related to failed transactions, incorrect balances, or
loan repayment issues. 


RELATION TO SDGs

This project relates to Sustainable Development Goal 9: Industry, Innovation and
Infrastructure, which promotes the development of reliable and sustainable technological
systems.

Mobile banking systems improve financial infrastructure by enabling secure digital 
financial services. By using an organized database system, banks can provide efficient
financial services, promote technological innovation, and support the growth of digital
banking in the Kenyan economy.

How the Proposed Database System Helps Solve the Problem
The proposed database system is designed to address those challenges by organizing 
banking data into structured entities and relations as shown in the ERD.
The system includes a Loan entity that stores information such as loan ID, loan amount,
payment dates, and loan status. This allows the bank to monitor loan repayments,
identify overdue loans, and manage credit records more effectively.
Authentication entity  manages login credentials such as usernames and passwords.
This ensures that only authorized users can access the system and reducing fraud and
security risks. Additionally, the Device entity records information about the devices
used to access the system, helping banks detect suspicious login activity from
unknown devices.

The system also improves transaction reliability by storing all financial activities
in the Transaction entity, which records details such as transaction ID, amount,
transaction type, date, and status. This ensures that transactions are properly
tracked and can be reviewed if problems occur.
To minimize system failures and delays, the database organizes data efficiently through
separate entities such as Client, Account, Wallet, and Transaction. This structured
design improves data retrieval speed and allows the system to handle large volumes
of financial records more effectively.

Finally, the system improves customer support and issue resolution by maintaining
complete transaction histories and account records. Bank administrators can easily
retrieve information about failed transactions, loan statuses, or account balances, 
allowing them to resolve customer issues more quickly and accurately.
Through these features, the proposed Mobile Banking Database System helps improve the
security, efficiency, and reliability of digital banking services in Kenya.

